--- PART 4: chi(q^2-1) CONNECTION ---
From algebra: copart > 0 iff chi((a+b)(b-a)) = chi(b^2-a^2) = chi(q^2-1) = ...
For q-resonance (qa=b): b^2-a^2 = a^2(q^2-1)
chi(b^2-a^2) = chi(a^2)*chi(q^2-1) = chi(q^2-1)

So: copart > 0 iff chi(q^2-1) = +1
    q^2-1 = (q-1)(q+1)
    chi(q^2-1) = chi(q-1)*chi(q+1)

CLAIM: copart > 0 iff chi(q-1)*chi(q+1) = +1
Let's verify this is equivalent to HYP-601:

  p=7: HYP-601 vs chi(q^2-1): 1/2 match
  p=11: HYP-601 vs chi(q^2-1): 2/4 match
  p=19: HYP-601 vs chi(q^2-1): 4/8 match
  p=23: HYP-601 vs chi(q^2-1): 5/10 match
  p=31: HYP-601 vs chi(q^2-1): 7/14 match
  p=43: HYP-601 vs chi(q^2-1): 10/20 match


--- PART 5: VERIFY chi(q-1)*chi(q+1) = chi(q^2-1) ---
This is just multiplicativity of chi. Always true.

So the copart theorem simplifies to:
  copart(q) > 0 iff chi(q^2-1) = +1
  i.e., (q-1)(q+1) is a QR mod p

But wait -- is this EQUIVALENT to HYP-601?
HYP-601: chi(q)=+1 => copart iff chi(q+1)=-1
         chi(q)=-1 => copart iff chi(q-1)=+1

Case 1: chi(q)=+1
  chi(q-1)*chi(q+1)=+1 means chi(q-1)=chi(q+1)
  q is odd, q-1 is even. For copart: chi(q+1)=-1
  If chi(q+1)=-1, then chi(q-1)=-1, product=+1. OK.
  If chi(q+1)=+1, then chi(q-1)=+1, product=+1. PROBLEM!
  Wait, product=+1 in BOTH cases if chi(q-1)=chi(q+1)!

So chi(q^2-1)=+1 does NOT reduce to HYP-601 directly.
Let me recheck...


